
[1]ravage

   RAV'AGE, n. [L. rapio.]

   1. Spoil; ruin; waste; destruction by violence, wither by men, beasts
   or physical causes; as the ravage of a lion; the ravages of fire or
   tempest; the ravages of an army.

   Would one think 'twene possible for love to make such ravage in a noble
   soul.

   2. Waste; ruin; destruction by decay; as the ravages of time.

                                RAV'AGE, v.t.

   1. To spoil; to plunder; to pillage; to sack.

   Already Cesar has ravag'd more than half the globe!

   2. To lay waste by any violent force; as, a flood or inundation ravages
   the meadows.

   The shatter'd forest and the ravag'd vale.

   3. to waste or destroy by eating; as fields ravaged by swarms of
   locusts.
